nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|A very interesting hand to bid. Let us go over it one bid at a time.  noi has several choices of 1@H, 1@D, and 2N. Once noi bids 1@H, 2@S is reasonable by roberta. However, I think sandy should bid 4@H, not 3@H. 3@H is somewhat of a misdesciption. It tends to show fewer hearts and more points. A bid of 4H by sandy is probably the best description of her hand. Basically, a good rule to follow is that if you have 5 card support for a known 5 card suit in partner's hand, it is almost always right to bid 4, regardless of how strong partner is. Therefore, since 1@H promises 5 hearts, sandy should bid 4 hearts, especially because her spade shortness is very valuable on this auction.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|now, given she bid 3H, why didn't I bid 3@S? The 3@S is certainly a safe bid by me, since I have a known 9 card fit at least. But I was afraid they might make 4 hearts, and I did not want to push them into 4 hearts by bidding 3@S. My general rule on partials is that I don't make a bid that will push them into a game they might not otherwise bid, unless I think they are going down. so I rarely bid 4@C or 4@D when the opponents have a major, unless I think 4 of the major is going down. And the same thing is true of bidding 3@S over 3@H. Here, however, noi correctly saw that she had a very good hand once pard raises hearts, and made a nice 4@H bid.|
